Toy Horse Case Assignment

Yanzi Cai, Ao Zhang, Sizhu Wu, Dong Li, Keyan Wang

Project Background

  • Conjoint analysis for toy horse company EarlyRiders.
  • Dataset
    • “conjointData” (ratings of different profiles, which refer to different attributes, provided by 200 individuals.Missing value included.)
    • “profilesData” (16 total profiles,attributes include price(119.99 and 139.99), size(18 and 26 inches), motion(Bouncing and Rocking), style(Racing and Glamour))
    • “repondentData” (age and gender of 200 respondents)
  • Current products
    • EarlyRiders: 18’‘Glamorous Rocking Horse and 18’’ Racing Rocking Horse, both at $139.99 (profile 13 and profile 5)
    • Competitor: 26’’ Racing Rocking Horse at $139.99
  • Mandate
    • Understanding market preferences in order to reviralize broader product line.
    • Taking advantage of differences across people to target new products or modify existing products to better target segments.

Analysis task

A. Use Regression to estimate the conjoint model at the individual level.
B. Conduct Benefit Segmentation via Cluster Analysis of Conjoint Part-Utilities.
C. Conduct a priori segmentation.
D. Simulate market shares for different product-line scenarios.

indiData = as.data.frame(matrix(NA,200,6))
colnames(indiData) = c("id","(intercept)","priceLow","sizeLarge","motionRocking","styleGlamour")
for (id in 1:200){
  data = conjointDataReg[conjointDataReg$ID == id,]
  lm = summary(lm(ratings~price+size+motion+style,data = data))
  indiData[id,1] = id
  indiData[id,2] = lm[[4]][1]
  indiData[id,3] = lm[[4]][2]
  indiData[id,4] = lm[[4]][3]
  indiData[id,5] = lm[[4]][4]
  indiData[id,6] = lm[[4]][5]
  lm = lm(ratings~price+size+motion+style,data = data)
  conjointData[conjointData$ID == id&is.na(conjointData$ratings),3] = predict(lm,conjointData[conjointData$ID == id& is.na(conjointData$ratings),3:7])
}

clustTest = function(toClust,print=TRUE,scale=TRUE,maxClusts=15,seed=12345,nstart=20,iter.max=100){
  if(scale){ toClust = scale(toClust);}
  set.seed(seed)
  wss <- (nrow(toClust)-1)*sum(apply(toClust,2,var))
  for (i in 2:maxClusts) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(toClust,centers=i,nstart=nstart,iter.max=iter.max)$withinss)
  gpw = fviz_nbclust(toClust,kmeans,method="wss",iter.max=iter.max,nstart=nstart,k.max=maxClusts) 
  pm1 = pamk(toClust,scaling=TRUE)
  gps = fviz_nbclust(toClust,kmeans,method="silhouette",iter.max=iter.max,nstart=nstart,k.max=maxClusts) 
  if(print){
    grid.arrange(gpw,gps, nrow = 1)
  }
  list(wss=wss,pm1=pm1$nc,gpw=gpw,gps=gps)
}
clustTest(indiDataNew)

runClusts = function(toClust,nClusts,print=TRUE,maxClusts=15,seed=12345,nstart=20,iter.max=100){
  if(length(nClusts)>4){
    warning("Using only first 4 elements of nClusts.")
  }
  kms=list(); ps=list();
  for(i in 1:4){
    kms[[i]] = kmeans(toClust,nClusts[i],iter.max = iter.max, nstart=nstart)
    ps[[i]] = fviz_cluster(kms[[i]], geom = "point", data = toClust) + ggtitle(paste("k =",nClusts[i]))
  }
  library(gridExtra)
  if(print){
    tmp = marrangeGrob(ps, nrow = 2,ncol=2)
    print(tmp)
  }
  list(kms=kms,ps=ps)
}

km = kmeans(indiDataNew,3,iter.max = 100, nstart=20)

plotClust = function(km,toClust,discPlot=FALSE){
  nc = length(km$size)
  if(discPlot){par(mfrow=c(2,2))}
  else {par(mfrow=c(3,1))}
  percsize = paste(1:nc," = ",format(km$size/sum(km$size)*100,digits=2),"%",sep="")
  pie(km$size,labels=percsize,col=1:nc)
  
  clusplot(toClust, km$cluster, color=TRUE, shade=TRUE,
           labels=2, lines=0,col.clus=1:nc); 
  
  if(discPlot){
    plotcluster(toClust, km$cluster,col=km$cluster); 
  }
  rng = range(km$centers)
  dist = rng[2]-rng[1]
  locs = km$centers+.05*dist*ifelse(km$centers>0,1,-1)
  bm = barplot(km$centers,beside=TRUE,col=1:nc,main="Cluster Means",ylim=rng+dist*c(-.1,.1))
  text(bm,locs,formatC(km$centers,format="f",digits=1))
}

plotClust(km,indiDataNew)

############### PART C ###############
  • Results interpretation:
    • Gender and age affect part-utilities while gender has a significant influence on segmentation.
    • 2 year old boys prefer low price, large size,racing and no preference for motion. The ideal product for 2 year old boys is 26" Racing Rocking Horse at $119.99.
    • 3-4 year old boys prefer low price, large size, bouncing and racing. The ideal product for 3-4 year old boys is 26" Racing Bouncing Horse at $119.99.
    • Both 2 year old girls and 3-4 year old girls prefer low price, large size, rocking and glamour. The ideal product for girls is 26" Rocking Glamorous Horse at $119.99.
  • Therefore, there’s another segment(prefer small size toy) we got from previous analysis that could not be recognized from A Prior Analysis since this segment has no gender/age difference.

#find max rating
simFCDecisions = function(scen,data,ascend=FALSE){
  test = data[,scen] 
  Matrix = matrix(0,200,length(test))
  colnames(Matrix) = colnames(test)
  test$max = 0
  if(ascend){
    for (y in 1:200){
      test$max[y] = min(test[y,])
    }
  } else {
    for (y in 1:200){
      test$max[y] = max(test[y,])
    }
  }
  for (r in 1:200){
    for (c in 1:(length(test)-1)){
      if(test[r,c]==test[r,"max"]){
        Matrix[r,c] = 1
      }
    }
  }
  Matrix = as.data.frame(Matrix)
  Matrix
}

calcUnitShares = function(decisions){
  colSums(decisions)/sum(decisions) 
}

simFCShares=function(scen,data,ascend=FALSE){
  decs = simFCDecisions(scen,data,ascend)
  calcUnitShares(decs)
}

scens3[[2]]=c(3,7,15)
scens3[[3]]=c(4,8,16)


simFCScenarios = function(scenarios,data,...){
  res = matrix(nrow=length(scenarios),ncol=length(data))
  for(i in 1:length(scenarios)){
    res[i, scenarios[[i]] ] = simFCShares(scenarios[[i]],data,...)
  }
  res = as.data.frame(res)
  names(res) = names(data)
  res
}

shareData1= simFCScenarios(scens,ratingData[,2:17])
shareDataCut1= shareData1[,c(2,5,7,8,11,13,15,16)]
shareData2= simFCScenarios(scens2,ratingData[,2:17])
shareDataCut2= shareData2[,c(2,5,7,8,11,13,15,16)]
shareData3= simFCScenarios(scens3,ratingData[,2:17])
shareDataCut3= shareData3[,c(3,4,5,7,8,13,15,16)]
############### PART D ###############
  • Results interpretation:
    • Plan A: Launch profile 3 and profile 15 in Year1 and change to profile 4 and profile 16 in Year 2. This is the best plan that can reach highest first year profit and also highest total profit for five years without cannibalization.
    • Plan B: Gain market share step by step by changing product line every year from Year1 to Year4. This plan takes competitor’s respond speed into account and expect that competitor would respond by lowering price in the fourth year rather than the second year.
